  abstract = {Background and Aim: Switzerland has a low post mortem organ donation\textbackslash nrate. Here we examine variables that are associated with the consent of\textbackslash nthe deceased's next of kin (NOK) for organ donation, which is a\textbackslash nprerequisite for donation in Switzerland.\textbackslash nMethods and Analysis: During one year, we registered information from\textbackslash nNOK of all deceased patients in Swiss intensive care units, who were\textbackslash napproached for consent to organ donation. We collected data on patient\textbackslash ndemographics, characteristics of NOK, factors related to the request\textbackslash nprocess and to the clinical setting. We analyzed the association of\textbackslash ncollected predictors with consent rate using univariable logistic\textbackslash nregression models; predictors with p-values {$<$}0.2 were selected for a\textbackslash nmultivariable logistic regression.\textbackslash nResults: Of 266 NOK approached for consent, consent was given in 137\textbackslash n(51.5\%) cases. In multivariable analysis, we found associations of\textbackslash nconsent rates with Swiss nationality (OR 3.09, 95\% CI: 1.46-6.54) and\textbackslash nGerman language area (OR 0.31, 95\% CI: 0.14-0.73). Consent rates tended\textbackslash nto be higher if a parent was present during the request (OR 1.76, 95\%\textbackslash nCI: 0.93-3.33) and if the request was done before brain death was\textbackslash nformally declared (OR 1.87, 95\% CI: 0.90-3.87).\textbackslash nConclusion: Establishing an atmosphere of trust between the medical\textbackslash nstaff putting forward a request and the NOK, allowing sufficient time\textbackslash nfor the NOK to consider donation, and respecting personal values and\textbackslash ncultural differences, could be of importance for increasing donation\textbackslash nrates. Additional measures are needed to address the pronounced\textbackslash ndifferences in consent rates between language regions.}
